Key takeaways.

A linked list is a chain of nodes where each node holds a value and a pointer to the next node. Nodes are scattered across the heap — not contiguous like array elements.

Index access is linear time, because you must walk the chain from the head. Insert and delete at a position you already have a reference to are constant time, because you only update one or two pointers.

A doubly linked list adds a previous pointer, giving you constant-time deletion when you hold a direct reference to the node. Sentinel nodes simplify all the edge cases.

To reverse a linked list, walk it once with three pointers, flipping each next pointer backward — linear time and constant space. And Floyd's algorithm uses fast and slow pointers to detect cycles in linear time with no extra memory — the same pattern finds the middle of a list.
